@PeteinSD Just because $TLT isn't trading with meme-stock fervor doesn't make it portfolio poison. The entire point of 60/40 is for one side to hedge the other during risk on/risk off periods. 60/40 failed last year, as this chart clearly shows when both stocks and bonds sold off. That ended last October for both assets. 

But I love the sentiment of "X is poison, while Y is only going up". Last year tech was poison and only energy went up. Now everyone loves tech, bonds are poison and we've got this braindead risk on FOMO mentality. 

👇 This won't continue indefinitely.

@DumspterDicks @TonyProTrading cost of borrowing is likely to be higher for corporates. 

Corporate bonds and treasury bonds *do not* trade the same way in times of stress (see chart above). Again, when spreads blow out in recession, borrowing gets really expensive for companies, meanwhile sovereign debt yields fall. And it's all because of risk. There is no default risk in a treasury (debt ceiling drama aside). So flight to safety kicks in and treasuries get a bid, particularly given treasury bonds collateralize the entire financial system which is a permanent bid of sorts. Not mortgages and not corporate debt. 

Duration has ALREADY gotten steamrolled, which is why we have a solvency problem in the banking sector. If you think the worst of the duration losses are over (I do, as does the bond market given curve inversion) then piling into $HYG or $LQD is riskier than say $TLT.

@FCFmaniac Yeah I'm just waiting, which is the hard part. The market will bottom on bad data, so one day I will flip bullish and start buying stocks while the economic data is still really shitty. But that will likely be after the labor market deteriorates, and/or we see stress in the corporate bond market and stocks nosedive with a Fed pivot. Right now it feels too much like walking out onto the street in front of a bus to pick up loose change. 

In the interim, my feed is filled with bulls (who I respect), declaring this a new bull market because they've stared at technicals on stock price charts for 6 months and are watching prices drift up as the $IEF/$LQD spread has come off its October peak and the $VIX has drifted lower. 

Fun Fact, the $VIX is now at the same low level (17) it was at when the market peaked in January 2022. Great buying opportunity! /s

@FCFmaniac Stock market is in large part a derivative of credit markets and corporate/treasury credit spreads have remained remarkably tight. Equity vol decoupled from junky credit last year too from where it would normally be. A lower vix lets stocks rise. So yes stocks are blissfully ignorant. 

I don't know the cause unless more hedging is moving over into day trades (0DTE) instead of longer term hedges which would get picked up in the $VIX. 

At some point though the treasury market will enter a bull-steepener and sovereign/corporate spreads ($IEF / $LQD) will finally blow out causing stocks to fall. Unless of course, it's truly different this time. $HYG $UVXY

@danielartrader Maybe rewatch the last couple minutes of the video. Loan default or non-performing loans isn't the only risk. Defaults aren't what brought down SVB. It was deposit flight, which forced them to sell assets from the balance sheet to raise cash, assets they were underwater on. That's what made $SIVB insolvent. 

Deposit outflow from small regional banks who are underwater on these CRE loans have the same problem if we see more deposit flight. And the BTFP bailout facility the Fed created does not accept CRE as collateral (at least at this point). 

But let's say this problem doesn't blow up in some big way. If you're a bank holding a bunch of impaired CRE, how likely are you to extend new loans to grow the economy? Do you even have the balance sheet capacity to do so?

@Mellow2022 @Piktrader Your first impression is correct, it has to do with bond convexity, which is how bond prices react to changes in yields. I posted about this yesterday comparing 3 different treasury ETFs: 

stocktwits.com/Forklift5909... 

You can actually somewhat see the convexity (sloped curve) in this plot of $TLT prices against long-term yields.

@AnchorsAweigh Sentiment has been terrible for a year now. If you tried to buy the bottom because of bad sentiment you would have lost money repeatedly. The AAii bull/bear thing mostly just follows market prices too. Turns out people get bearish when prices drop and bullish when prices rise. Sentiment can get much worse. 

And the fundamentals are not at all like the bottom in March 2009, or 2020. We had credit spreads blow out in both cases. This is the biggest remaining risk we haven't seen yet. Look at this chart. The SHTF when the Fed cuts and credit spreads widen. Then you buy. Not here, not because we're 10% off October lows, or because technicals say this or that. It doesn't matter. Maybe they cut this week? Maybe we're near the end with a big drop? 

Give me a 35+ $VIX and a widening of spreads (surge in red line below) and then I'll start buying.

@AnchorsAweigh this chart is kind of useless without knowing the maturity. I'd bet most shorts are in short-term paper, which is still making money as the Fed hikes. Shorting long-term paper (TLT) has been a losing trade since October. $TLT has now rallied off the lows through 2 rate hikes now, because the long-term paper doesn't respond to hikes, it responds to inflation and growth. Fed only influences short term rates. 

@ThereAreNoSpoons  As the Fed cuts rates the entire yield curve shifts down vertically. All bonds rally. 

To straighten the curve, they need to get short term rates lower than long term. So if long term rates like a 30 year fall from 3.4% down to 1.25% (as happened around covid recession), then short term rates need to fall below 1.25%. 

After yields across the curve bottom is when the cycle resets and long-term yields then move up again pricing in higher growth and inflation/reflation of the economy.

@Curusasoaso A lot of people say it's because of lockdowns. We'll see. 

It's one thing to close your doors and still have customers waiting outside for you to reopen. Quite another to reopen and find you have no customers. 

The latter I think is more likely given the global rate hiking, inventory builds and softening demand. China's economy will bounce back but I don't think it's going to be this V-shape grand reopening everyone peddles, even though $EM has bounced hard off the lows, mainly because the $DXY / dollar rolled over.

@isam1974 @Mellow2022 Falling container volumes like that is not normal. But it starts making a lot more sense when you factor in retailers with too much inventory into softening demand, so they stop ordering as much which is reflected in declining PMIs. 

Real retail sales were basically flat last year as consumers aren't buying more, they're simply paying more for what they buy. And they even started pulling back from that as real (inflation adjusted) retail sales started ramping down last Fall, even as inflation has basically gone sideways for 6 months now. 

Tell me again there isn't a recession on the horizon. $TLT

