@howardlindzon @howardstory October 24th remains the low in $TMF and $TLT so far. October 21st was the largest volume in $TMF's history: 

stocktwits.com/Forklift5909... 

I'm starting to think this marked the low in bonds. So if you got in late October, you had a great entry point.

@Mellow2022 This is why I was buying on the way down. Now everyone is waiting for a pull-back so they can jump in. I don't ever recommend to chase but there's no guarantee we'll close that gap. Not all gaps get filled, or at least they may not get filled for a long time. 

For example, there's a gap at $170 on $TLT back in August of 2020. Price gapped down below the 20 day sma and that was the start of the reversal from the top. It's called a breakaway gap: 

investopedia.com/terms/b/br...

@JLInvest Yup, I've been extremely skeptical of the "strong consumer balance sheet" argument. If consumers are so flush then why are they trading down to house brands and lower end retail? 

cnn.com/2022/11/15/business... 

It's typically *not* a good sign when stores like $WMT, $DG and $DLTR are thriving (nothing against those stocks).

@JLInvest The trend in tightening financial conditions (widening credit spreads) has been moving up since last October which is when stocks got very volatile and shortly thereafter the market peaked. So if you think the trend broke today, then you must believe the bear market is over and it's time to get ultra-long. 

$SPY is practically a derivative of $IEF / $LQD. 

I don't think bond spreads are in a safe spot until the Fed cuts and we see how corporate bonds react. If they move together, we may avoid a big crash like in 2020. Today for example both IEF and LQD rallied. Where we have problems is when one moves higher than the other. During 2009 and 2020, treasuries ($IEF) got bid while corporate bonds ($LQD) were dumped. Stock market crashed.

@JLInvest This hasn't updated for today, so maybe there will be a big move lower. But financial conditions are still extremely tight when judged through the spread between corporate bonds and treasuries. We're still hovering near 2019 highs. 

$IEF / $LQD is a good substitute. 

The real recovery/bull market kicks off when this trend breaks lower and financial conditions truly ease through tighter spreads. I'm still expecting some sort of spike up at some point like we had in 2020 or during the GFC. Treasury yields went to the floor, corporate yields went through the roof, big flush in stocks. But then it was over.

@CouponBaller Yes I read it weeks ago. I don't have much interest in "new world order" type of financial prognostications like this though. It reminds me too much of things like "peak oil". You start with a flawed premise and all the predictions which follow end up wrong. And it's very hard to say where the world will be in 20 or 30 years given the rate of change at this period in human history. 

A couple months back Zoltan Poszar from $CS was claiming the world would be going back to some neo-bartering system because commodities are the future. If they are, it doesn't really matter in the short term. Or maybe they're not? So I don't find multi-decade economic forecasts useful for investing or trading. 

But it's a long article, is there something specific you were wondering about? His take on government bonds is completely wrong, btw, at least in the short term. It doesn't even make sense if you think the government will artificially send yields lower. That's bullish from here.

@Mellow2022 $SHY is the 1 - 3 year treasury ETF. It only has a $16 trading range though at most. I'm not entirely sure why. You would have to use leverage through options to magnify returns for when rates are eventually cut. On the flip side, it's a pretty safe place to park cash as it's only down around $6 through this hiking regime. 

TLT has larger price swings. That's primarily why I'm buying that, as it's down over 40% from the highs. 

You can see on this chart SHY, TLT and Fed Funds rate flipped upside down. Typically the Fed hikes gradually, then cuts rapidly. So bonds slowly lose value, then crash upwards. Since they procrastinated last year, they're front-loading their hikes to catch up which is speeding up the move down in bonds. But I still expect the typical crash back up when they inevitably cut again.
